nd of dissembling language.Robyn Malo argues that relic discourse was employed in order to critique mainstream religious practice, explore the consequences of rhetorical dissimulation, and consider the effect on the socially disadvantaged of lavish expenditure on shrines. The work thus uses the literary study of relics to address issues of clerical and lay cultures, orthodoxy and heterodoxy, and writing and reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aRelics in literature. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266325140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442663251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442663251.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK